A '''roll call''' is the process of checking who is in attendance, usually by calling out and checking off their names.

Places where roll calls are often held include schools, military camps, and prisons. Roll calls are also standard procedure after buildings are evacuated because of a fire alarm, bomb threat, etc. 

In a legislature, a '''roll call''' vote is one in which the members' names are read aloud, after which they declare their votes; thus, how individual members voted can be determined. Alternatives include a voice vote.